episodes.description:
This scene in the 1984 movie Ghostbusters is stunning and memorable for its irony. The Bill Murray character announces, when someone questions his methods, “Back off, I’m a scientist”. The claim is so surprising because there is no evidence for the theory of busting ghosts, merely the claim of expertise. 
As scientifically trained professionals, we recognize the importance of linking conclusions to the evidence that supports them. To avoid casting ourselves with the likes of ghostbusters, we need to be very careful about the pronouncements we make and our reasons for making them.

The character Lancaster Dodd in the movie The Master (2012) identifies as a writer, doctor, nuclear physicist, theoretical philosopher but, above all, he says "I'm a man, a hopelessly enquisitive man just like you". 

This is the way Hubbard would ingratiate himself to others: a subtle form of complement where you tell someone who is clearly not what you are describing them as that they're a certain way. It establishes a kind of mutual illusion of the person being better than they really are, which they are happy to ascribe to and even start believing themselves (e.g. being enquisitive) even though it never would have occurred to them to think of themselves that way.
